							<hr width="100%" size="1" class="hrcolor" />
							<div class="post">The switch/case statement is used when you are comparing an integer value against a number of integer constants:<br /><br />If your code looks something like this:<br /><div class="codeheader">Code:</div><div class="code">int x = f();<br /><br />if (x == 1)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;do the stuff for 1;<br />else<br />if (x == 2)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;do the stuff for 2;<br />else<br />if (x == 5)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;do the stuff for 5;<br />else<br />if (x == 17)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;do the stuff for 17;<br /></div><br />you can re-write it to be this:<br /><br /><div class="codeheader">Code:</div><div class="code">int x = f();<br />switch (x)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; {<br />case 1:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;do the stuff for 1;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;break;<br />case 2:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;do the stuff for 2;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;break;<br />case 5:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;do the stuff for 5;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;break;<br />case 17:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;do the stuff for 17;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;break;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br /></div></div>
						</td>
